<doc id="316826" wikidata="Q493941" url="?curid=316826" title="Fibration">
<text>The notion of a fibration generalizes the notion of a fiber bundle and plays an important role in algebraic topology, a branch of mathematics.

Fibrations are used, for example, in Postnikov systems or obstruction theory.

In this article, all mappings are continuous mappings between topological spaces.

== Formal definitions ==

=== Homotopy lifting property ===
A mapping formula_1 satisfies the homotopy lifting property for a space formula_2 if:

* for every homotopy formula_3 and
* for every mapping (also called lift) formula_4 lifting formula_5 (i.e. formula_6)

there exists a (not necessarily unique) homotopy formula_7 lifting formula_8 (i.e. formula_9) with formula_10

The following commutative diagram shows the situation: 
=== Fibration ===
A fibration (also called Hurewicz fibration) is a mapping formula_1 satisfying the homotopy lifting property for all spaces formula_12 The space formula_13 is called base space and the space formula_14 is called total space. The fiber over formula_15 is the subspace formula_16
=== Serre fibration ===
A Serre fibration (also called weak fibration) is a mapping formula_1 satisfying the homotopy lifting property for all CW-complexes. 

Every Hurewicz fibration is a Serre fibration.

=== Quasifibration ===
A mapping formula_1 is called quasifibration, if for every formula_19 formula_20 and formula_21 holds that the induced mapping formula_22 is an isomorphism.

Every Serre fibration is a quasifibration.

== Examples ==

* The projection onto the first factor formula_23 is a fibration. That is, trivial bundles are fibrations.
* Every covering formula_1 is a fibration. Specifically, for every homotopy formula_3 and every lift formula_4 there exists a uniquely defined lift formula_27 with formula_28 
* Every fiber bundle formula_1 satisfies the homotopy lifting property for every CW-complex.
* A fiber bundle with a paracompact and Hausdorff base space satisfies the homotopy lifting property for all spaces.
* An example of a fibration which is not a fiber bundle is given by the mapping formula_30 induced by the inclusion formula_31 where formula_32 formula_2 a topological space and formula_34 is the space of all continuous mappings with the compact-open topology.
* The Hopf fibration formula_35 is a non-trivial fiber bundle and, specifically, a Serre fibration.

== Basic concepts ==

=== Fiber homotopy equivalence ===
A mapping formula_36 between total spaces of two fibrations formula_37 and formula_38 with the same base space is a fibration homomorphism if the following diagram commutes:

The mapping formula_39 is a fiber homotopy equivalence if in addition a fibration homomorphism formula_40 exists, such that the mappings formula_41 and formula_42 are homotopic, by fibration homomorphisms, to the identities formula_43 and formula_44 

=== Pullback fibration ===
Given a fibration formula_1 and a mapping formula_46, the mapping formula_47 is a fibration, where formula_48 is the pullback and the projections of formula_49 onto formula_50 and formula_14 yield the following commutative diagram:

The fibration formula_52 is called the pullback fibration or induced fibration.

=== Pathspace fibration ===
With the pathspace construction, any continuous mapping can be extended to a fibration by enlarging its domain to a homotopy equivalent space. This fibration is called pathspace fibration.

The total space formula_53 of the pathspace fibration for a continuous mapping formula_46 between topological spaces consists of pairs formula_55 with formula_56 and paths formula_57 with starting point formula_58 where formula_59 is the unit interval. The space formula_60 carries the subspace topology of formula_61 where formula_62 describes the space of all mappings formula_63 and carries the compact-open topology.

The pathspace fibration is given by the mapping formula_64 with formula_65 The fiber formula_66 is also called the homotopy fiber of formula_39 and consists of the pairs formula_55 with formula_56 and paths formula_70 where formula_71 and formula_72 holds.

For the special case of the inclusion of the base point formula_73, an important example of the pathspace fibration emerges. The total space formula_74 consists of all paths in formula_13 which starts at formula_76 This space is denoted by formula_77 and is called path space. The pathspace fibration formula_78 maps each path to its endpoint, hence the fiber formula_79 consists of all closed paths. The fiber is denoted by formula_80 and is called loop space.

== Properties ==

* The fibers formula_81 over formula_15 are homotopy equivalent for each path component of formula_83
* For a homotopy formula_84 the pullback fibrations formula_85 and formula_86 are fiber homotopy equivalent. 
* If the base space formula_13 is contractible, then the fibration formula_1 is fiber homotopy equivalent to the product fibration formula_89
* The pathspace fibration of a fibration formula_1 is very similar to itself. More precisely, the inclusion formula_91 is a fiber homotopy equivalence.
* For a fibration formula_1 with fiber formula_93 and contractible total space, there is a weak homotopy equivalence formula_94

